# Big Picture: How HFT connects to a Trading System

A real **HFT (High-Frequency Trading)** algorithm does NOT directly “touch” the exchange core.

Instead, it connects through a **low-latency pipeline**:

[Market Data Feed]  --->  [HFT Algo]  --->  [Order Gateway]  --->  [Exchange Matching Engine]
         ↑                                                        ↓
         <------------------- Execution Reports -------------------

---

# Step-by-step flow (real system)

## 1. Market Data Feed (Input to HFT)

Exchange sends:

* Trades
* Order book updates (Level 1 / Level 2)

Example:

Bid: 100 x 10
Ask: 101 x 12

👉 HFT listens using:

* TCP / UDP multicast
* Binary protocols (FAST, FIX, ITCH)

---

## 2. HFT Algorithm (Decision Engine)

This is your **core C++ logic**.

It:

* Maintains local order book
* Runs strategy (microseconds level)

Example logic:

if (bestBid > myFairPrice) {
    sendSellOrder();
}

Key:

* No DB calls
* No malloc (pre-allocated memory)
* Lock-free / cache-friendly

---

## 3. Order Gateway (Bridge to Exchange)

HFT **does NOT send directly to matching engine**.

It sends to an **Order Gateway** using:

* FIX protocol (common)
* Binary low-latency APIs (proprietary)

Example FIX message:

NewOrderSingle:
Symbol=INFY
Side=BUY
Price=100
Qty=10

---

## 4. Exchange Matching Engine

This is what you are building in your C++ project.

It:

* Matches buy/sell orders
* Updates order book

---

## 5. Execution Reports (Feedback loop)

Exchange → HFT:

Order Accepted
Order Filled
Order Rejected

HFT reacts instantly:

if (filled) {
    hedgePosition();
}

---

# Real-Time Loop (Critical Insight)

HFT is NOT one-time execution.

It’s a **continuous loop**:

Receive Market Data
        ↓
Update Local Book
        ↓
Run Strategy
        ↓
Send Order
        ↓
Receive Fill
        ↓
Adjust Strategy
        ↓
Repeat (microseconds)

